/*The following iterative sequence is defined for the set of positive integers:
n → n/2 (n is even)
n → 3n + 1 (n is odd)
Using the rule above and starting with 13, we generate the following sequence:
13 → 40 → 20 → 10 → 5 → 16 → 8 → 4 → 2 → 1
It can be seen that this sequence (starting at 13 and finishing at 1) contains 10 terms. 
Although it has not been proved yet (Collatz Problem), it is thought that all starting numbers finish at 1.
Which starting number, under one million, produces the longest chain?
NOTE: Once the chain starts the terms are allowed to go above one million.*/
public class Problem14 {

	public static void main(String[] args) {
		System.out.println(test(999999));
		findLongestChain2();
		findLongestChain();

	}

	
	private static void findLongestChain2(){
		int[] numbersInChain=new int[999_999];
		numbersInChain[1] = 1;
		long number=0;
		int sequenceLength=0;
		int startingNumber =0;
		for (int i = 2; i < 1_000_000 ; i++) {
		    number = i;
		    int k = 0;
		    while (number != 1 && number >= i) {
		        k++;
		        if ((number % 2) == 0) {
		            number = number / 2;
		        } else {
		            number = number * 3 + 1;
		        }
		    }
		    //Store result in cache
		    numbersInChain[i] = k + numbersInChain[number];
		 
		    //Check if number is the best solution
		    if (numbersInChain[i] > sequenceLength) {
		        sequenceLength = numbersInChain[i];
		        startingNumber = i;
		    }
		}
		System.out.println(startingNumber+ " "+ sequenceLength);
	}
	
	private static void findLongestChain(){
		int max=0, number=0;
		for (int i = 0; i < 1_000_000; i++) {
			if (test(i)>max) {
				max=test(i);
				number=i;
			}
		}
		System.out.println(number+ " " +max);
	}
	
	private static int test(long number){
		int count=1;
		while(number > 1){
			if (number % 2 ==0) {
				number /= 2;			
				count++;
			}else {
				number=3*number+1;
				count++;
			}
		}
		return count;
	}
}
